      <li xml:id="sym_determinant">
        <p>
          A <em>2 by 2 matrix over</em>
    <idx><h>matrix</h></idx>
          <m>\mathbb{R}</m> is a rectangular array of four real numbers arranged in two rows and two columns.
          We usually write this array inside brackets
          (or parentheses)
          as follows:
          <me>
            A = \left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} a \amp  b  \\ c \amp  d \end{array}  } \right]
          </me>,
          where  <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>,
          and  <m>d</m>  are real numbers.
          The <em>determinant</em>
    <idx><h>determinant</h></idx>
    <idx><h>matrix</h><h>determinant</h></idx>
          of the 2 by 2 matrix  <m>A</m>,
          denoted by  <m>\det( A )</m> ,  is defined as
          <me>
            \det( A ) = ad - bc
          </me>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate the determinant of each of the following matrices:
                <me>
                  \left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} 3 \amp  5  \\ 4 \amp  1 \end{array}  } \right],\;\left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} 1 \amp  0  \\ 0 \amp  7 \end{array}  } \right],\;\text{ and } \left[ {\begin{array}{*{20}c} 3 \amp  { - 2}  \\ 5 \amp  0 \end{array}  } \right]
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>\mathcal{M}_2( \R )</m> be the set of all 2 by 2 matrices over <m>\R</m>.
                The mathematical process of finding the determinant of a 2 by 2 matrix over <m>\R</m> can be thought of as a function.
                Explain carefully how to do so,
